      <hedline>
        <hl1>Liberty, Round 2</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Frances Anderton</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Anderton, Frances</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mike McNeilly, who started to paint 12-story Statue of Liberty on Westwood Medical Building on Wilshire Boulevard in Los Angeles, area where zoning prohibits commerical billboards, has finished his painting despite pending court case barring art; photo (Currents column) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Drivers on Wilshire Boulevard are doing double takes as a wall keeps changing its image. For Memorial Day last year, Mike McNeilly started to paint a 12-story Statue of Liberty on the Westwood Medical Building, in an area where zoning prohibits commercial billboards. It was meant to honor war veterans, the artist said,  but after a city councilman took action, work was suspended and the matter ended up in court. Not that Mr. McNeilly waited around for a ruling. After painting the word ''censored'' over the half-finished work, he returned in time for Memorial Day last month with a second take, right, on Liberty.</p>
      </block>
